1
00:00:00,961 --> 00:00:02,401
(WIND BLOWING)

2
00:00:11,161 --> 00:00:13,841
Quite an Arctic storm
blowing out there. Hm!

3
00:00:13,921 --> 00:00:15,921
Come along, Polly,
my child, with my cloak.

4
00:00:16,001 --> 00:00:18,321
Hey, Doctor, you've got
the most fantastic wardrobe.

5
00:00:18,401 --> 00:00:21,481
Yes. We don't know
what we're in for outside there.

6
00:00:21,561 --> 00:00:23,881
Pretty soon we shall be having visitors.

7
00:00:24,961 --> 00:00:26,201
(BEEPING)

8
00:00:26,281 --> 00:00:27,961
You're different.
You've got no feelings.

9
00:00:28,081 --> 00:00:30,841
I do not understand that word.

10
00:00:30,921 --> 00:00:33,921
Emotions. Love, pride, hate,

11
00:00:34,561 --> 00:00:35,561
fear!

12
00:00:37,001 --> 00:00:38,961
Have you no emotions, sir?

13
00:00:40,681 --> 00:00:42,121
What's happened to you, Doctor?

14
00:00:42,241 --> 00:00:46,321
I guess this old body of mine
is wearing a bit thin.

15
00:00:48,721 --> 00:00:51,201
BEN: Doctor. Wakey, wakey.
It's all over now.

16
00:00:54,201 --> 00:00:55,321
(CREAKING)

17
00:00:56,601 --> 00:00:57,601
No.

18
00:00:58,841 --> 00:01:00,681
It isn't all over.

19
00:01:01,881 --> 00:01:04,561
It's far from being all over.

20
00:01:05,161 --> 00:01:06,161
What are you talking about?

21
00:01:06,241 --> 00:01:09,121
I must get back to the TARDIS.

22
00:01:15,441 --> 00:01:16,921
I can't go through with it.

23
00:01:17,281 --> 00:01:19,641
I will fight it.

24
00:01:21,001 --> 00:01:22,601
I will not change.

25
00:01:22,921 --> 00:01:25,161
Hello? Is someone there.

26
00:01:27,121 --> 00:01:28,361
Hello?

27
00:01:33,881 --> 00:01:36,081
-Who is that?
-I'm the Doctor.

28
00:01:37,321 --> 00:01:39,401
Oh, I don't think so.

29
00:01:39,481 --> 00:01:42,361
No. (CHUCKLES) Dear me, no.

30
00:01:43,441 --> 00:01:45,641
You may be a doctor.

31
00:01:45,721 --> 00:01:48,641
But I am the Doctor.

32
00:01:48,721 --> 00:01:52,401
The original, you might say.

33
00:01:55,521 --> 00:01:56,521
You?

34
00:01:59,281 --> 00:02:01,681
How can it be you?

35
00:02:01,761 --> 00:02:04,401
-Do I know you, sir?
-This is the South Pole.

36
00:02:04,521 --> 00:02:05,841
We're at the South Pole.

37
00:02:05,961 --> 00:02:08,281
Of course, we are.
Don't you know that?

38
00:02:08,361 --> 00:02:09,441
This is where it happened.

39
00:02:09,561 --> 00:02:11,481
Where what happened?

40
00:02:11,721 --> 00:02:13,641
This is it.

41
00:02:16,001 --> 00:02:17,721
The very first time

42
00:02:18,281 --> 00:02:21,961
that I... Well, you...
We regenerated.

43
00:02:22,561 --> 00:02:24,561
You're mid-regeneration, aren't you?

44
00:02:25,521 --> 00:02:28,081
Your face. It's all over the place.

45
00:02:28,441 --> 00:02:30,041
But you're trying to hold it back.

46
00:02:31,121 --> 00:02:33,681
What do you know of regeneration?

47
00:02:34,001 --> 00:02:35,281
Are you a Time Lord?

48
00:02:35,361 --> 00:02:36,761
You know who I am. You must.

49
00:02:36,841 --> 00:02:37,841
(CHUCKLES)

50
00:02:39,081 --> 00:02:42,561
Have you come to take the ship back?

51
00:02:43,761 --> 00:02:46,841
The ship. You still call it a ship.

52
00:02:46,961 --> 00:02:49,761
Oh, dear.
What have you done to it?

53
00:02:51,001 --> 00:02:52,601
Nothing. The windows.

54
00:02:53,161 --> 00:02:55,001
-I don't remember this.
-They're the wrong size!

55
00:02:55,081 --> 00:02:56,721
I don't remember
trying not to change.

56
00:02:56,801 --> 00:02:59,321
-Not back then.
-I'm sure it's changed. Look at it!

57
00:03:00,281 --> 00:03:03,081
It seems to have expanded.

58
00:03:03,161 --> 00:03:05,161
Well, it's all those years
of bigger on the inside.

59
00:03:05,241 --> 00:03:08,441
You try sucking your tummy in that long.
Why are you trying not to regenerate?

60
00:03:08,561 --> 00:03:10,761
I have the courage and the right

61
00:03:10,881 --> 00:03:13,601
to live and die as myself.

62
00:03:13,681 --> 00:03:15,401
Too late. It's started.

63
00:03:16,201 --> 00:03:18,721
A few minutes ago,
you were weak as a kitten, right?

64
00:03:19,241 --> 00:03:23,801
Now, you're fine.
We're in a state of grace, both of us.

65
00:03:23,921 --> 00:03:26,601
But it won't last long.
We have a choice.

66
00:03:27,361 --> 00:03:29,241
Either we change and go on,

67
00:03:30,321 --> 00:03:31,801
or we die as we are.

68
00:03:34,081 --> 00:03:35,361
But, if you...

69
00:03:36,361 --> 00:03:37,521
If you die here...

70
00:03:39,561 --> 00:03:42,201
If your future never happens,

71
00:03:42,281 --> 00:03:44,801
if you don't do the things
that you are supposed to do,

72
00:03:44,921 --> 00:03:46,481
the consequences could be...

73
00:03:49,441 --> 00:03:51,241
-The snow.
-Snow?

74
00:03:51,681 --> 00:03:52,961
Look at it!

75
00:03:54,841 --> 00:03:56,601
How extraordinary.

76
00:04:08,641 --> 00:04:09,801
Everything's stopped.

77
00:04:10,881 --> 00:04:12,001
Why?

78
00:04:13,001 --> 00:04:14,281
Maybe it's us.

79
00:04:15,401 --> 00:04:16,681
Maybe it's something else.

80
00:04:17,681 --> 00:04:22,401
But somehow, something
has gone very wrong with time.

81
00:04:22,521 --> 00:04:23,641
MAN: Hello?

82
00:04:27,241 --> 00:04:28,601
Sorry.

83
00:04:29,881 --> 00:04:31,601
I'm so sorry.

84
00:04:32,921 --> 00:04:35,961
I don't suppose
either of you is a doctor?

85
00:04:38,121 --> 00:04:39,121
You trying to be funny?

86
00:04:40,521 --> 00:04:42,521
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

87
00:05:26,601 --> 00:05:29,121
CAPTAIN: There is
something I should like to say.

88
00:05:29,201 --> 00:05:30,201
That is,

89
00:05:30,601 --> 00:05:33,281
there is something I should
very much like you to understand

90
00:05:36,961 --> 00:05:40,521
I do not have
the slightest desire to kill you.

91
00:05:41,801 --> 00:05:44,281
The only reason I would do so
is self-defence.

92
00:05:46,121 --> 00:05:50,321
However, since you're aware
I might kill you in self-defence,

93
00:05:50,521 --> 00:05:53,841
there is the strong possibility
you will kill me in self-defence.

94
00:05:54,121 --> 00:05:55,121
(PANTING)

95
00:05:56,961 --> 00:06:00,481
It does rather make me wish
you understood English.

96
00:06:00,601 --> 00:06:02,081
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

97
00:06:04,761 --> 00:06:06,361
Or that I spoke German.

98
00:06:09,681 --> 00:06:11,361
War is hell, eh?

99
00:06:14,321 --> 00:06:15,721
(SHELL WHISTLING)

100
00:06:16,601 --> 00:06:17,601
(EXPLOSION)

101
00:07:00,401 --> 00:07:02,361
(FIRE CRACKLING)

102
00:07:28,801 --> 00:07:29,801
(YELLS)

103
00:07:34,561 --> 00:07:37,561
GLASS WOMAN: Time line error.
There is a time line error.

104
00:07:37,641 --> 00:07:38,921
Time line error.

105
00:07:39,001 --> 00:07:40,441
There is a time line error.

106
00:07:40,841 --> 00:07:42,001
(COUGHING)

107
00:07:42,081 --> 00:07:43,521
(PANTING)

108
00:07:54,721 --> 00:07:56,201
DOCTOR: Everything stopped.

109
00:07:57,001 --> 00:07:58,881
FIRST DOCTOR: But why?

110
00:07:59,201 --> 00:08:00,521
DOCTOR: Maybe it's us.

111
00:08:01,081 --> 00:08:02,641
Maybe it's something else.

112
00:08:03,041 --> 00:08:06,561
But somehow, something has gone
very wrong with time.

113
00:08:06,881 --> 00:08:07,881
Hello.

114
00:08:11,961 --> 00:08:12,961
Sorry.

115
00:08:14,841 --> 00:08:15,961
I'm so sorry.

116
00:08:16,361 --> 00:08:19,441
I don't suppose
either of you is a doctor?

117
00:08:20,561 --> 00:08:21,761
You trying to be funny?

118
00:08:23,881 --> 00:08:25,201
She's coming.

119
00:08:26,121 --> 00:08:28,081
She's coming.

120
00:08:28,161 --> 00:08:29,161
It's her.

121
00:08:31,801 --> 00:08:33,441
FIRST DOCTOR: Not human, I think.

122
00:08:33,761 --> 00:08:37,121
State your planet of origin
and your intentions.

123
00:08:37,281 --> 00:08:40,641
This is Earth,
a level five civilisation.

124
00:08:40,721 --> 00:08:41,961
And it is protected.

125
00:08:42,041 --> 00:08:43,681
It's what?

126
00:08:44,321 --> 00:08:46,641
Oh, okay.
That doesn't usually work.

127
00:08:46,721 --> 00:08:48,521
Protected by whom?

128
00:08:48,681 --> 00:08:51,401
Oh, it is early days. Isn't it?

129
00:08:54,161 --> 00:08:56,801
May I suggest for your own safety,

130
00:08:56,881 --> 00:09:00,081
you step on board my ship?

131
00:09:00,961 --> 00:09:02,121
What ship?

132
00:09:02,201 --> 00:09:04,041
He means, "Get inside the box."

133
00:09:04,121 --> 00:09:07,241
A little snug from this angle.

134
00:09:07,321 --> 00:09:10,441
But you might be in for a surp...

135
00:09:12,681 --> 00:09:13,681
My TARDIS!

136
00:09:14,801 --> 00:09:16,161
Look at my TARDIS!

137
00:09:16,241 --> 00:09:17,761
This is impossible.

138
00:09:17,841 --> 00:09:19,281
Have I been burgled?

139
00:09:19,361 --> 00:09:22,201
-It's... But it's...
-It's hideous.

140
00:09:22,281 --> 00:09:25,201
Bigger on the inside
than it is on the outside.

141
00:09:25,281 --> 00:09:27,001
You know, I thought it probably was.

142
00:09:27,641 --> 00:09:29,361
Glad it's not just me.

143
00:09:30,641 --> 00:09:31,681
What is this place?

144
00:09:31,761 --> 00:09:36,641
This place is, or ought to be,
my TARDIS.

145
00:09:38,081 --> 00:09:40,561
Technically, that is your TARDIS.

146
00:09:40,961 --> 00:09:43,001
It's about 70 feet that way.

147
00:09:43,081 --> 00:09:44,121
See?

148
00:09:44,201 --> 00:09:46,761
Always remember where you parked.
It's gonna come up a lot.

149
00:09:46,841 --> 00:09:48,201
Is this madness?

150
00:09:50,041 --> 00:09:51,161
Am I going mad?

151
00:09:51,441 --> 00:09:55,481
Madness? Well, you're an officer
from World War One at the South Pole

152
00:09:55,561 --> 00:09:57,561
being pursued by an alien
through frozen time.

153
00:09:57,641 --> 00:09:59,281
(FIRST DOCTOR CHUCKLES)

154
00:09:59,641 --> 00:10:01,241
Madness was never this good.

155
00:10:01,881 --> 00:10:03,081
World War One?

156
00:10:03,761 --> 00:10:05,881
Judging by the uniform, yes.

157
00:10:06,281 --> 00:10:07,561
Yes, but...

158
00:10:08,881 --> 00:10:11,281
What do you mean, "One"?

159
00:10:13,681 --> 00:10:15,321
Oh, sorry, spoilers.

160
00:10:15,441 --> 00:10:16,721
Enough of this.

161
00:10:17,241 --> 00:10:18,401
Who are you?

162
00:10:18,761 --> 00:10:21,081
Um... You know who I am.

163
00:10:21,161 --> 00:10:22,641
You knew the moment you saw me.

164
00:10:22,721 --> 00:10:25,561
I'd say stop being an idiot,
but I kind of know what's coming.

165
00:10:25,801 --> 00:10:31,041
I assure you, I do not have
the faintest idea who you are.

166
00:10:31,121 --> 00:10:33,681
Well, I know who you are.

167
00:10:33,761 --> 00:10:35,841
Is anyone going
to explain what's going on?

168
00:10:37,201 --> 00:10:38,201
DOCTOR: Snap.

169
00:10:43,561 --> 00:10:45,321
You are me.

170
00:10:46,201 --> 00:10:47,681
No. No!

171
00:10:47,761 --> 00:10:50,761
Yes. Yes, I'm very much afraid so.

172
00:10:51,521 --> 00:10:54,961
Do I become you?

173
00:10:55,041 --> 00:10:57,921
Well, there's a few false starts,
but you get there in the end.

174
00:10:58,921 --> 00:11:00,801
But, I thought...

175
00:11:01,401 --> 00:11:02,401
What?

176
00:11:02,481 --> 00:11:07,801
Well, I assumed I'd get younger.

177
00:11:08,281 --> 00:11:09,841
I am younger!

178
00:11:10,401 --> 00:11:14,281
You know, I really don't think
I'm completely following.

179
00:11:14,801 --> 00:11:17,521
-Oh. Oh, dear.
-Oh, you're in shock!

180
00:11:17,601 --> 00:11:19,121
Let me help you.

181
00:11:19,401 --> 00:11:21,001
Brandy.

182
00:11:21,081 --> 00:11:22,681
Get him brandy.
Do you have any?

183
00:11:22,761 --> 00:11:24,641
I had some somewhere.

184
00:11:24,721 --> 00:11:27,041
-Hang on.
-Sit down here, my boy.

185
00:11:27,361 --> 00:11:29,161
Collect your wits.

186
00:11:29,801 --> 00:11:30,961
CAPTAIN: Who are you people?

187
00:11:31,241 --> 00:11:34,761
I am the Doctor and this is my...

188
00:11:34,841 --> 00:11:36,121
It's complicated, actually.

189
00:11:36,201 --> 00:11:38,281
-I am also...
-...my nurse.

190
00:11:39,921 --> 00:11:40,961
Excuse me?

191
00:11:41,041 --> 00:11:43,841
I realise that seems
a little improbable.

192
00:11:43,921 --> 00:11:45,521
-Yes.
-Because he's a man.

193
00:11:45,601 --> 00:11:46,601
What?

194
00:11:46,681 --> 00:11:50,161
Older gentlemen, like women,
can be put to use.

195
00:11:50,241 --> 00:11:52,361
You can't... You can't
say things like that.

196
00:11:52,441 --> 00:11:53,521
Can't 1?

197
00:11:53,841 --> 00:11:54,841
Says who?

198
00:11:54,921 --> 00:11:57,361
Just about everyone you're going to meet
for the rest of your life. Here.

199
00:12:00,801 --> 00:12:02,681
Have you had some of this?

200
00:12:03,081 --> 00:12:06,281
Well, you know,
I may have snuck a glass

201
00:12:06,361 --> 00:12:09,321
at some point in the last 1500 years.

202
00:12:09,401 --> 00:12:11,001
It's been rock and roll.

203
00:12:12,081 --> 00:12:13,361
Here you are.

204
00:12:13,441 --> 00:12:16,161
Get this down you.
You'll feel a lot better.

205
00:12:16,241 --> 00:12:17,401
-Thank you.
-Yes.

206
00:12:17,481 --> 00:12:20,241
FIRST DOCTOR: I, erm...
I don't understand any of this.

207
00:12:20,521 --> 00:12:22,321
Well, of course you understand.

208
00:12:22,401 --> 00:12:24,561
I am your future self.

209
00:12:24,801 --> 00:12:26,081
Are you indeed?

210
00:12:26,161 --> 00:12:29,361
And I suppose this is
meant to be my TARDIS?

211
00:12:29,761 --> 00:12:30,761
Our TARDIS.

212
00:12:30,841 --> 00:12:32,241
What's wrong with the lights?

213
00:12:32,401 --> 00:12:33,601
It's supposed to be like this.

214
00:12:33,721 --> 00:12:34,721
Why?

215
00:12:34,841 --> 00:12:35,961
It's atmospheric.

216
00:12:36,321 --> 00:12:39,921
Atmospheric?
This is the flight deck

217
00:12:40,001 --> 00:12:43,601
of the most powerful space-time
machine in the known universe,

218
00:12:43,681 --> 00:12:45,841
not a restaurant for the French.

219
00:12:47,441 --> 00:12:49,601
Good Lord. What is that?

220
00:12:49,761 --> 00:12:53,001
Oh. Look what someone
has accidentally left here.

221
00:12:53,081 --> 00:12:56,561
I say!
It's some sort of guitar, isn't it?

222
00:12:56,641 --> 00:12:57,961
-Is it yours?
-No.

223
00:12:58,041 --> 00:13:01,121
It appears to have
been played quite recently.

224
00:13:01,361 --> 00:13:03,641
It's the only thing here
that's been cleaned.

225
00:13:05,201 --> 00:13:08,761
In fact, this whole place
could do with a good dusting.

226
00:13:08,841 --> 00:13:11,681
Obviously, Polly isn't around any more.

227
00:13:12,601 --> 00:13:16,121
Please, please.
Please stop saying things like that.

228
00:13:17,641 --> 00:13:19,121
(THUDDING)

229
00:13:26,321 --> 00:13:27,761
(PANTING)

230
00:13:40,441 --> 00:13:41,641
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

231
00:13:44,241 --> 00:13:45,561
I can't get the engines to start.

232
00:13:45,641 --> 00:13:47,041
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

233
00:13:47,521 --> 00:13:49,881
There's some kind of signal
blocking the command path.

234
00:13:52,481 --> 00:13:53,601
(REVVING)

235
00:13:54,841 --> 00:13:56,121
FEMALE VOICE: Exit your capsule.

236
00:13:56,761 --> 00:13:59,761
The Chamber of the Dead awaits you.

237
00:14:00,481 --> 00:14:02,761
DOCTOR: I'll fix the engines
while you keep her talking.

238
00:14:04,961 --> 00:14:06,201
Fields up.

239
00:14:06,721 --> 00:14:08,361
(DOOR RATTLING)

240
00:14:13,401 --> 00:14:14,761
(DOOR CREAKING)

241
00:14:22,321 --> 00:14:23,841
Look around you.

242
00:14:27,721 --> 00:14:29,081
(BEEPING)

243
00:14:32,921 --> 00:14:35,561
You stand
in the Chamber of the Dead.

244
00:14:37,001 --> 00:14:39,001
You are known to all here

245
00:14:39,601 --> 00:14:42,201
for you are the Doctor of War.

246
00:14:44,401 --> 00:14:45,481
No, no.

247
00:14:45,561 --> 00:14:47,961
The Doctor, yes.

248
00:14:48,041 --> 00:14:53,001
But the Doctor of War?
Never, Ma'am. Never.

249
00:14:54,921 --> 00:14:56,441
We offer you a gift.

250
00:14:56,521 --> 00:14:58,881
Return to us
the human on your TARDIS.

251
00:14:58,961 --> 00:15:02,241
And in exchange
you may speak with her again.

252
00:15:02,321 --> 00:15:03,921
Speak with whom?

253
00:15:04,361 --> 00:15:05,361
(DOOR RATTLING)

254
00:15:14,521 --> 00:15:17,641
Young lady, who are you?

255
00:15:20,761 --> 00:15:21,761
Is he here?

256
00:15:22,641 --> 00:15:24,001
Is the Doctor here?

257
00:15:25,881 --> 00:15:27,001
BILL: Doctor!

258
00:15:29,241 --> 00:15:30,561
(LAUGHING)

259
00:15:31,881 --> 00:15:33,121
I knew it!

260
00:15:33,321 --> 00:15:34,641
I did! I knew it!

261
00:15:34,721 --> 00:15:37,521
I knew you couldn't be dead.
You don't have the concentration.

262
00:15:43,121 --> 00:15:44,121
Doctor?

263
00:15:48,161 --> 00:15:49,401
What are you doing?

264
00:15:49,481 --> 00:15:50,481
(BEEPING)

265
00:15:50,561 --> 00:15:51,921
Just keep still, please.

266
00:15:53,321 --> 00:15:54,561
Bill Potts?

267
00:15:54,881 --> 00:15:55,881
Yeah.

268
00:15:56,641 --> 00:15:59,281
My friend Bill Potts
was turned into a Cyberman.

269
00:16:01,041 --> 00:16:02,241
She gave her life

270
00:16:03,481 --> 00:16:05,761
so that people
she barely knew could live.

271
00:16:06,881 --> 00:16:11,721
So, let's be clear.
Nobody imitates Bill Potts.

272
00:16:11,801 --> 00:16:14,121
Nobody mocks Bill Potts.

273
00:16:15,081 --> 00:16:16,761
Bill Potts

274
00:16:16,841 --> 00:16:18,721
is standing right in front of you.

275
00:16:19,401 --> 00:16:21,161
How is that even possible?

276
00:16:22,841 --> 00:16:25,841
Well, long story short,
I totally pulled.

277
00:16:26,121 --> 00:16:28,681
You did what?

278
00:16:30,041 --> 00:16:32,401
Heather. Do you remember,
the girl in the puddle?

279
00:16:32,561 --> 00:16:34,121
Well, she showed up.

280
00:16:34,201 --> 00:16:35,601
She came for me.

281
00:16:35,721 --> 00:16:36,921
How romantic.

282
00:16:38,241 --> 00:16:39,361
Where is she?

283
00:16:42,281 --> 00:16:43,521
Well, she's...

284
00:16:46,281 --> 00:16:49,041
-She's...
-And how did you get here?

285
00:16:50,081 --> 00:16:51,521
I don't...

286
00:16:52,641 --> 00:16:54,721
-I can't...
-You can't remember. I bet you can't.

287
00:16:54,801 --> 00:16:56,601
(BEEPING)

288
00:16:57,401 --> 00:17:00,521
That device. What is it?

289
00:17:01,561 --> 00:17:03,041
It's a sonic screwdriver.

290
00:17:03,121 --> 00:17:05,081
A what screwdriver?

291
00:17:06,161 --> 00:17:08,441
It's really a very good job.

292
00:17:08,561 --> 00:17:10,801
An audio screwdriver?

293
00:17:10,921 --> 00:17:13,561
There are only three
low-key markers

294
00:17:14,041 --> 00:17:15,681
indicating that she's a duplicate.

295
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:17,441
I'm not a duplicate.

296
00:17:17,601 --> 00:17:21,761
So, who has been stealing
the faces of the dead?

297
00:17:41,881 --> 00:17:45,841
Time travel technology, eh? Obviously.

298
00:17:45,921 --> 00:17:47,801
DOCTOR: From the far future.

299
00:17:48,481 --> 00:17:49,961
I know.

300
00:17:54,401 --> 00:17:56,681
-Sunglasses?
-They're sonic.

301
00:17:57,001 --> 00:17:58,361
Indoors?

302
00:18:05,001 --> 00:18:07,121
So, what are you?

303
00:18:07,241 --> 00:18:11,041
We are what awaits
at the end of every life.

304
00:18:13,361 --> 00:18:18,361
As every living soul dies,
so we will appear.

305
00:18:18,441 --> 00:18:22,641
We take from you what we need and
return you to the moment of your death.

306
00:18:23,561 --> 00:18:26,601
We are testimony.

307
00:18:30,961 --> 00:18:33,401
DOCTOR: You come
from the distant future?

308
00:18:33,481 --> 00:18:35,841
You travel back in time,
you find people,

309
00:18:35,921 --> 00:18:38,361
at the exact point of death and what?

310
00:18:38,441 --> 00:18:40,801
You harvest something from them?

311
00:18:40,881 --> 00:18:41,881
Yes.

312
00:18:42,561 --> 00:18:46,121
On behalf of the dying,
what is it that we have

313
00:18:46,241 --> 00:18:47,841
that the future needs so badly?

314
00:18:47,921 --> 00:18:51,641
And what is any of this to do
with a World War One Captain

315
00:18:51,721 --> 00:18:55,081
landing at the South Pole
in the wrong decade?

316
00:18:55,161 --> 00:18:59,041
We were returning him to the appointed
time and place of his death.

317
00:18:59,121 --> 00:19:02,921
An error in the time line ejected him
into the wrong time zone.

318
00:19:03,481 --> 00:19:06,801
Now, his death must proceed
as history demands.

319
00:19:07,441 --> 00:19:08,681
If I may.

320
00:19:11,441 --> 00:19:13,241
Who were you?

321
00:19:13,321 --> 00:19:15,561
-She wasn't anyone.
-(BEEPING)

322
00:19:15,641 --> 00:19:18,241
She's a computer generated interface

323
00:19:18,441 --> 00:19:21,401
connected to a multiform
inter-phasing...

324
00:19:21,521 --> 00:19:26,201
Oh, for heaven's sake, will you put
that ridiculous buzzing toy away

325
00:19:26,281 --> 00:19:27,881
and look at the woman?

326
00:19:27,961 --> 00:19:30,241
You see? Her face.

327
00:19:30,841 --> 00:19:34,281
It's very slightly asymmetrical.

328
00:19:34,401 --> 00:19:37,921
If it were computer generated,
it wouldn't produce that effect.

329
00:19:38,321 --> 00:19:39,601
Yes!

330
00:19:39,921 --> 00:19:42,241
You're absolutely right.
I should've noticed that.

331
00:19:42,321 --> 00:19:44,681
Well, it might help
if you could see properly.

332
00:19:47,441 --> 00:19:50,761
Excuse me? Doctor?

333
00:19:52,081 --> 00:19:53,361
Get back inside.

334
00:19:53,481 --> 00:19:55,601
I'm not quite sure,

335
00:19:55,721 --> 00:19:57,881
but it seemed to me
that this young lady's life

336
00:19:58,001 --> 00:20:00,441
was being offered
in exchange for my own.

337
00:20:00,921 --> 00:20:06,561
Now as it happens, I think my number
is pretty much up anyway.

338
00:20:06,641 --> 00:20:10,161
What are you talking about?
Doctor, what is he talking about?

339
00:20:10,241 --> 00:20:14,041
So, might as well
make it count for something, eh?

340
00:20:14,121 --> 00:20:18,081
I should be happy to take your place
if that would resolve the situation.

341
00:20:18,161 --> 00:20:19,721
GLASS WOMAN: Accepted.

342
00:20:20,881 --> 00:20:23,121
(SCOFFS) That is...
That is not happening.

343
00:20:23,201 --> 00:20:24,961
That's totally not happening.

344
00:20:26,281 --> 00:20:27,641
Agreed?

345
00:20:27,721 --> 00:20:29,481
Tell me what to do then.

346
00:20:30,081 --> 00:20:32,041
Bill Potts would tell me what to do.

347
00:20:32,121 --> 00:20:33,841
Do what you always do.

348
00:20:35,241 --> 00:20:37,281
Serve at the pleasure of the human race.

349
00:20:41,241 --> 00:20:45,561
Here's what's going to happen.
First, I'm going to escape.

350
00:20:45,641 --> 00:20:47,801
-You, with me.
-Where are we going?

351
00:20:47,881 --> 00:20:49,721
Escape is not possible.

352
00:20:49,801 --> 00:20:52,161
It is possible and it is happening.

353
00:20:52,241 --> 00:20:54,001
And I'm taking Bill
and the Captain with me.

354
00:20:54,081 --> 00:20:56,841
Why are you advertising your intentions?

355
00:20:56,921 --> 00:20:58,921
Can't you stop boasting for a moment?

356
00:20:59,001 --> 00:21:00,561
Mr Pastry, too. I could do with a laugh.

357
00:21:00,641 --> 00:21:02,601
GLASS WOMAN: Escape is not possible.

358
00:21:02,681 --> 00:21:05,521
Oh, I'm going to do
way more than escape.

359
00:21:05,601 --> 00:21:08,361
I'm going to find out who you are
and what you are doing,

360
00:21:08,441 --> 00:21:11,681
and if I don't like it, I will come back
and I will stop you.

361
00:21:11,761 --> 00:21:13,601
I will stop all of you.

362
00:21:13,681 --> 00:21:16,041
Who the hell do you think you are?

363
00:21:16,121 --> 00:21:18,841
-The Doctor.
-I am the Doctor.

364
00:21:18,921 --> 00:21:21,801
Who you are, I cannot begin to imagine.

365
00:21:21,881 --> 00:21:23,961
GLASS WOMAN:
Then let us show you, Doctor.

366
00:21:24,041 --> 00:21:26,281
See who you will become.

367
00:21:29,081 --> 00:21:31,881
-DALEK: Doctor!
-Exterminate!

368
00:21:31,961 --> 00:21:34,001
You will be assimilated!

369
00:21:34,081 --> 00:21:35,761
DOCTOR: No, no, no.
That's not a good idea.

370
00:21:35,841 --> 00:21:37,161
They all die.

371
00:21:37,241 --> 00:21:42,161
GLASS WOMAN: The Doctor has walked
in blood through all of time and space.

372
00:21:42,241 --> 00:21:43,961
The Doctor has many names.

373
00:21:44,041 --> 00:21:46,721
MAN: The destroyer of the world!

374
00:21:46,801 --> 00:21:49,321
GLASS WOMAN: The imp of the pandorica.

375
00:21:49,401 --> 00:21:51,281
The shadow of the Vale yard.

376
00:21:51,681 --> 00:21:54,121
The beast of Trenzalore.

377
00:21:54,201 --> 00:21:56,601
The butcher of Skull Moon.

378
00:21:56,681 --> 00:21:58,401
The last tree of Garsennon.

379
00:21:58,481 --> 00:22:00,361
The destroyer of Skaro.

380
00:22:00,441 --> 00:22:03,601
He is the Doctor of War.

381
00:22:06,761 --> 00:22:08,481
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

382
00:22:10,201 --> 00:22:11,881
What... What was that?

383
00:22:11,961 --> 00:22:13,961
To be fair, they cut out all the jokes.

384
00:22:15,641 --> 00:22:17,921
-Do what I do when I do it.
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

385
00:22:19,121 --> 00:22:20,121
(GRUNTS)

386
00:22:23,961 --> 00:22:25,321
Jump!

387
00:22:27,041 --> 00:22:29,441
(ALL GRUNTING)

388
00:22:40,401 --> 00:22:42,121
GLASS WOMAN: They are not escaping!

389
00:22:44,961 --> 00:22:46,801
(GRUNTING)

390
00:22:51,041 --> 00:22:52,881
(GRUNTS)

391
00:22:56,881 --> 00:22:59,001
(PANTING)

392
00:22:59,961 --> 00:23:01,281
(GRUNTS)

393
00:23:03,241 --> 00:23:05,801
(BOTH GRUNT)

394
00:23:06,761 --> 00:23:07,761
DOCTOR: Jump!

395
00:23:07,881 --> 00:23:10,281
(ALL GRUNTING)

396
00:23:19,721 --> 00:23:21,721
-BILL: What do we do now?
-Run!

397
00:23:21,801 --> 00:23:23,721
Where? They've got the TARDIS.

398
00:23:23,801 --> 00:23:25,761
Yes. That's exactly
what they're supposed to think.

399
00:23:25,841 --> 00:23:27,361
Yeah, but they do, though. Look.

400
00:23:27,441 --> 00:23:30,481
DOCTOR: They've got my TARDIS.
Over to you, Mary Berry.

401
00:23:30,561 --> 00:23:31,561
Come on.

402
00:23:34,761 --> 00:23:39,121
Doctor, is that another TARDIS?

403
00:23:39,201 --> 00:23:40,601
No.

404
00:23:41,001 --> 00:23:43,041
No, it's another of the same TARDIS.

405
00:23:49,561 --> 00:23:51,281
Hang on. The windows are the wrong size.

406
00:23:51,361 --> 00:23:52,801
Inside, quickly.

407
00:23:56,281 --> 00:23:57,281
Take off, now.

408
00:23:57,961 --> 00:23:59,401
Deep space, anywhere.

409
00:24:03,721 --> 00:24:05,961
(RHYTHMIC WHIRRING)

410
00:24:08,681 --> 00:24:11,321
Tell you what. These police boxes,

411
00:24:11,401 --> 00:24:13,121
they're ever so good, aren't they?

412
00:24:13,201 --> 00:24:15,961
The navigation systems
don't function properly.

413
00:24:16,041 --> 00:24:20,121
I'm unable to programme our flight
with any accuracy.

414
00:24:21,921 --> 00:24:25,961
So, my dear,
I presume you travel with him?

415
00:24:26,241 --> 00:24:28,841
Used to. Kind of miss it.

416
00:24:29,321 --> 00:24:31,801
Well, he clearly misses you.

417
00:24:32,321 --> 00:24:36,201
That ship of his is in dire need
of a good spring clean.

418
00:24:36,281 --> 00:24:38,881
No, no, stop, stop... Look, look.
Oh, look, look, look.

419
00:24:38,961 --> 00:24:40,161
Look at the lovely... The astral map.

420
00:24:40,241 --> 00:24:41,441
Look at the lovely blinking lights.

421
00:24:41,521 --> 00:24:43,241
Look at that. (WHISTLES)

422
00:24:43,321 --> 00:24:45,081
BILL: He's you.

423
00:24:46,401 --> 00:24:49,441
He is, isn't he? He's you.
He's one of your old faces.

424
00:24:50,641 --> 00:24:54,481
I find I'm lagging behind
a tiny bit again. (STAMMERS)

425
00:24:55,241 --> 00:24:58,321
Not those again, I forbid it.

426
00:24:58,401 --> 00:25:01,481
There you go. I was right.

427
00:25:01,561 --> 00:25:03,681
-Asymmetrical.
-I said that.

428
00:25:03,761 --> 00:25:05,521
Same difference.

429
00:25:07,761 --> 00:25:11,081
If her face
was based on a human original,

430
00:25:11,161 --> 00:25:12,961
perhaps identifying who that was

431
00:25:13,041 --> 00:25:15,361
will tell us what we need to know
about testimony.

432
00:25:15,441 --> 00:25:17,961
Er, why am I wearing these?

433
00:25:18,041 --> 00:25:19,481
Because I love it.

434
00:25:19,561 --> 00:25:21,521
Never take those off.

435
00:25:21,601 --> 00:25:23,001
What's "browser history"?

436
00:25:24,641 --> 00:25:28,481
I'm trying to match her face
in the TARDIS data bank.

437
00:25:29,081 --> 00:25:31,041
But there's hardly anything in it yet.

438
00:25:31,121 --> 00:25:33,241
We need a bigger database.

439
00:25:33,841 --> 00:25:36,401
Possibly the Matrix on Gallifrey.

440
00:25:38,161 --> 00:25:42,041
No. We need something bigger
than the Matrix.

441
00:25:42,601 --> 00:25:46,361
CAPTAIN: So, basically we're trying
to track the Glass Lady, yes?

442
00:25:46,441 --> 00:25:49,761
BILL: Basically.
FIRST DOCTOR: A striking creature.

443
00:25:53,001 --> 00:25:55,041
Quite beautiful really, isn't she?

444
00:25:55,121 --> 00:25:58,361
Yeah, if you like ladies made of glass.

445
00:25:58,441 --> 00:26:02,841
Well, aren't all ladies
made of glass in a way?

446
00:26:02,921 --> 00:26:04,401
(BOTH LAUGHING)

447
00:26:04,481 --> 00:26:06,721
Very good, sir, very good.

448
00:26:06,801 --> 00:26:08,281
Are we now?

449
00:26:08,921 --> 00:26:11,921
Oh, my dear,
I hope it doesn't offend you to know

450
00:26:12,001 --> 00:26:16,561
that I have had some experience
of the, er, fairer sex.

451
00:26:16,641 --> 00:26:18,321
Me too.

452
00:26:20,281 --> 00:26:21,481
Good Lord.

453
00:26:21,641 --> 00:26:22,961
(RUMBLING)

454
00:26:23,601 --> 00:26:25,441
(WHIRRING)

455
00:26:29,001 --> 00:26:30,321
Where are we?

456
00:26:30,401 --> 00:26:34,161
FIRST DOCTOR: But you steered the ship,
you piloted her perfectly.

457
00:26:34,241 --> 00:26:37,961
We are at
the very centre of the universe.

458
00:26:38,041 --> 00:26:40,041
DOCTOR: Out there is the most
comprehensive database

459
00:26:40,121 --> 00:26:41,121
of all life anywhere.

460
00:26:43,601 --> 00:26:45,401
There is just one little problem.

461
00:26:45,481 --> 00:26:47,241
Which is?

462
00:26:47,401 --> 00:26:48,841
It wants to kill me.

463
00:26:49,801 --> 00:26:51,121
(SIGHS)

464
00:26:53,881 --> 00:26:55,921
(CREATURES SCREECHING)

465
00:27:03,441 --> 00:27:05,281
The Weapon Forges of Villengard.

466
00:27:05,361 --> 00:27:07,281
Once the nightmare
of the seven galaxies.

467
00:27:08,401 --> 00:27:11,921
Now home to the dispossessed.

468
00:27:12,001 --> 00:27:14,881
I say, I think there's something
moving over here.

469
00:27:14,961 --> 00:27:16,961
Step away, please.

470
00:27:17,041 --> 00:27:18,321
Probably just rats.

471
00:27:18,761 --> 00:27:20,401
-I'm used to rats.
-(CREATURES SCURRYING)

472
00:27:20,521 --> 00:27:22,921
-(SCREAMING)
-(CREATURE SCREECHING)

473
00:27:25,521 --> 00:27:26,841
(GRUNTS)

474
00:27:28,601 --> 00:27:31,161
-(GASPING)
-Deep breaths, deep breaths.

475
00:27:31,241 --> 00:27:32,721
Just breathe, Captain, you'll be fine.

476
00:27:32,801 --> 00:27:35,041
FIRST DOCTOR: That creature,
it looked familiar.

477
00:27:35,121 --> 00:27:37,921
It's mutated a bit, but, yes,
I should think it did.

478
00:27:38,001 --> 00:27:40,441
Come along, my dear chap,
you'll be fine.

479
00:27:40,521 --> 00:27:43,401
-Get him into the TARDIS.
-What are those things?

480
00:27:45,001 --> 00:27:46,841
DOCTOR: Er...

481
00:27:50,041 --> 00:27:51,281
What we came here for.

482
00:27:52,281 --> 00:27:55,001
-The biggest database in the galaxy.
-(CREATURES SCREECHING)

483
00:27:55,081 --> 00:27:56,321
They'll settle down in a moment.

484
00:27:57,921 --> 00:28:02,481
So, do we talk to them?
Ask them questions? How does it work?

485
00:28:02,561 --> 00:28:04,881
-We don't do anything, I do.
-(BILL PROTESTING)

486
00:28:04,961 --> 00:28:06,761
-No, no, no...
-You're going to wait in the TARDIS.

487
00:28:06,841 --> 00:28:09,641
-But why?
-You need to look after the Captain.

488
00:28:09,841 --> 00:28:13,361
You're lying.
You think I'm a duplicate. A trick.

489
00:28:13,521 --> 00:28:16,321
I don't know what I think.

490
00:28:16,401 --> 00:28:19,921
But if there's the slightest chance
that Bill Potts is alive,

491
00:28:21,241 --> 00:28:25,961
and standing in front of me,
then I will not under any circumstances,

492
00:28:26,121 --> 00:28:27,641
put her life in danger again.

493
00:28:27,841 --> 00:28:31,921
Seriously? You're looking right at me
and you don't even know I'm here?

494
00:28:32,561 --> 00:28:35,521
Correct. I ask you to respect that.

495
00:28:36,001 --> 00:28:37,681
-And respect me.
-You're an arse.

496
00:28:37,961 --> 00:28:42,121
(STAMMERING)
You're a stupid bloody arse.

497
00:28:42,321 --> 00:28:44,401
As I've always respected you.

498
00:28:46,761 --> 00:28:50,281
If I hear any more language
like that from you, young lady,

499
00:28:50,361 --> 00:28:53,081
you're in for
a jolly good smacked bottom.

500
00:28:55,881 --> 00:28:57,041
(GASPS SOFTLY)

501
00:28:59,641 --> 00:29:01,401
Can we just pretend that
that never happened?

502
00:29:01,481 --> 00:29:02,921
I'm a broad-minded girl.

503
00:29:03,001 --> 00:29:06,801
I mean, I know we have this whole
professor/student thing going on...

504
00:29:06,881 --> 00:29:09,441
Can we just never ever
talk about this again?

505
00:29:09,561 --> 00:29:11,521
Yeah, I hope we talk about it loads.

506
00:29:13,961 --> 00:29:17,761
(CHUCKLES) I hope we spend years
laughing about it.

507
00:29:24,361 --> 00:29:25,481
Come back alive.

508
00:29:25,681 --> 00:29:26,921
Be here when I do.

509
00:29:34,721 --> 00:29:38,241
Perhaps another nip of brandy.

510
00:29:39,321 --> 00:29:43,201
Mmm. So that's where it went.

511
00:29:45,241 --> 00:29:46,961
I'll look after him.

512
00:29:47,081 --> 00:29:49,241
Good girl. Quite right.

513
00:29:49,321 --> 00:29:53,361
Now, young lady,
I don't want to have to repeat myself.

514
00:29:53,441 --> 00:29:55,281
I don't think any of us want that.

515
00:29:55,441 --> 00:29:57,441
I'll see you both presently.

516
00:29:59,921 --> 00:30:01,201
Brandy?

517
00:30:01,641 --> 00:30:02,881
Please.

518
00:30:09,121 --> 00:30:10,721
(BIRDS SCREECHING)

519
00:30:17,321 --> 00:30:20,401
FIRST DOCTOR:
These creatures, what are they?

520
00:30:20,641 --> 00:30:22,001
DOCTOR: Old friends of ours.

521
00:30:22,561 --> 00:30:24,361
But they've
really come out of their shell.

522
00:30:24,441 --> 00:30:26,201
FIRST DOCTOR: Out of their shell?

523
00:30:26,721 --> 00:30:27,761
You all right?

524
00:30:27,841 --> 00:30:29,321
(GASPING)

525
00:30:30,561 --> 00:30:33,041
I'll be... I'll be fine in a moment.

526
00:30:33,281 --> 00:30:34,641
Well, what's the matter?

527
00:30:34,721 --> 00:30:37,361
I died a few hours ago
then I refused to regenerate.

528
00:30:37,441 --> 00:30:39,761
It catches up with you.
You know, it's like a big lunch.

529
00:30:39,841 --> 00:30:41,761
I did exactly the same.

530
00:30:42,321 --> 00:30:43,721
I know you did. But why?

531
00:30:44,761 --> 00:30:46,041
I don't remember this.

532
00:30:46,761 --> 00:30:48,601
Why are you refusing the regeneration?

533
00:30:48,681 --> 00:30:49,801
Fear.

534
00:30:51,041 --> 00:30:53,441
I'm afraid. Very, very afraid.

535
00:30:54,641 --> 00:30:57,241
I don't normally admit that
to, er, anyone else.

536
00:30:58,321 --> 00:31:00,601
Don't worry.
Technically you still haven't.

537
00:31:02,201 --> 00:31:03,241
Why are you?

538
00:31:09,081 --> 00:31:10,081
(DOCTOR GROANS)

539
00:31:10,201 --> 00:31:11,881
FIRST DOCTOR: There's something
in that tower!

540
00:31:14,121 --> 00:31:15,321
DOCTOR: Must be my friend.

541
00:31:16,041 --> 00:31:18,041
FIRST DOCTOR:
Why do you call it your friend?

542
00:31:19,161 --> 00:31:20,361
(BOTH GROAN)

543
00:31:21,001 --> 00:31:22,801
DOCTOR: He's got a great big gun.

544
00:31:23,161 --> 00:31:25,121
Are you suggesting I insult him?

545
00:31:28,281 --> 00:31:29,481
Just scan me.

546
00:31:30,281 --> 00:31:32,001
Go on, scan me.

547
00:31:33,161 --> 00:31:34,761
'Cause I've got big news for you.

548
00:31:35,601 --> 00:31:37,081
I'm dying!

549
00:31:45,961 --> 00:31:47,241
See, it's true.

550
00:31:48,441 --> 00:31:49,441
(MAKES POPPING NOISE)

551
00:31:49,641 --> 00:31:50,641
Dying.

552
00:31:52,641 --> 00:31:56,841
Now, be honest with yourself,
wouldn't you like to see that up close?

553
00:32:06,201 --> 00:32:08,201
Come on, up and at 'em,
Corporal Jones.

554
00:32:08,281 --> 00:32:09,441
I don't know.

555
00:32:12,521 --> 00:32:13,561
Funny thing,

556
00:32:14,841 --> 00:32:16,441
I wasn't afraid in the crater.

557
00:32:18,281 --> 00:32:19,801
One doesn't want to die, of course,

558
00:32:19,881 --> 00:32:21,521
but one gets in a certain frame of mind,

559
00:32:21,601 --> 00:32:24,601
one pulls oneself together
and gets on with the matter in hand.

560
00:32:27,121 --> 00:32:29,961
Big shock for everyone.
Back in Cromer of course.

561
00:32:30,321 --> 00:32:32,521
BILL: You have family?

562
00:32:32,601 --> 00:32:34,361
My wife will miss me.

563
00:32:35,721 --> 00:32:37,721
That's perfectly natural.

564
00:32:38,161 --> 00:32:40,201
But she's a solid woman,
remarkably solid.

565
00:32:40,281 --> 00:32:41,881
And my boys...

566
00:32:43,521 --> 00:32:44,761
Well...

567
00:32:45,801 --> 00:32:48,721
Sons are supposed to
move on from their fathers.

568
00:32:48,801 --> 00:32:50,041
It's the proper way.

569
00:32:50,561 --> 00:32:52,121
BILL: Of course.

570
00:32:53,001 --> 00:32:54,721
Trouble is, I thought I'd been rescued.

571
00:32:55,641 --> 00:32:58,241
Felt rather like a miracle, in fact.

572
00:33:00,961 --> 00:33:03,281
But I do have this feeling
they're going to put me back.

573
00:33:04,161 --> 00:33:05,401
Back in that crater.

574
00:33:06,481 --> 00:33:07,921
In time to die.

575
00:33:09,041 --> 00:33:10,401
And you see,

576
00:33:11,561 --> 00:33:13,081
I'm not ready any more.

577
00:33:14,761 --> 00:33:16,281
I've lost the idea of it.

578
00:33:18,681 --> 00:33:20,161
That's the trouble with hope.

579
00:33:21,961 --> 00:33:23,481
Makes one awfully frightened.

580
00:33:24,001 --> 00:33:25,001
(CHUCKLES)

581
00:33:26,201 --> 00:33:28,761
I must sound like
the most dreadful coward.

582
00:33:38,601 --> 00:33:41,001
Okay, I'd better go up alone.

583
00:33:41,081 --> 00:33:42,761
I won't hear of it.

584
00:33:44,521 --> 00:33:48,161
That thing up there
won't miss the chance to kill me twice.

585
00:33:48,241 --> 00:33:50,241
The paradox would
rip the universe apart.

586
00:33:51,041 --> 00:33:54,201
And you know how much hard work it is
putting it back together again.

587
00:33:54,281 --> 00:33:56,441
You keep a lookout down here.

588
00:33:56,521 --> 00:33:58,441
Oh, if you insist.

589
00:34:43,561 --> 00:34:45,921
You know what? You're
a bit of a legend these days.

590
00:34:47,521 --> 00:34:49,321
Not everyone believes it.

591
00:34:54,721 --> 00:34:57,641
People don't think that it could happen.

592
00:34:58,881 --> 00:35:02,321
Someone like you could
turn against your own kind.

593
00:35:02,401 --> 00:35:04,481
Because your kind don't do that.

594
00:35:05,841 --> 00:35:07,521
Out of their shells.

595
00:35:11,521 --> 00:35:13,401
Because people don't believe

596
00:35:14,401 --> 00:35:16,241
there could be any such thing

597
00:35:19,641 --> 00:35:21,161
as a good Dalek.

598
00:35:23,641 --> 00:35:25,881
I am not a good Dalek!

599
00:35:25,961 --> 00:35:28,001
You are a good Dalek!

600
00:35:29,241 --> 00:35:30,841
(DOCTOR GRUNTS)

601
00:35:32,041 --> 00:35:34,441
Oh. Hello, my dear.

602
00:35:34,921 --> 00:35:37,841
Now, Rusty, you know that I'm dying.

603
00:35:38,561 --> 00:35:41,321
If you don't want me to go off and die
somewhere else where you can't watch,

604
00:35:41,401 --> 00:35:43,281
you're gonna have to
stop shooting at me.

605
00:35:45,121 --> 00:35:47,961
I agree to your terms.

606
00:35:48,321 --> 00:35:50,081
Well, I'm going to need some proof.

607
00:35:51,681 --> 00:35:52,961
(METAL SCRAPING)

608
00:35:54,841 --> 00:35:56,841
(CRACKLING)

609
00:36:00,601 --> 00:36:01,801
You know what?

610
00:36:01,881 --> 00:36:04,441
You're the very first Dalek
that ever got naked for me.

611
00:36:04,521 --> 00:36:05,801
(CRACKLING)

612
00:36:05,881 --> 00:36:08,881
You're the first one, yeah,
like the original version of the Doctor?

613
00:36:08,961 --> 00:36:11,041
My dear, you should
get back to the ship.

614
00:36:11,121 --> 00:36:12,561
This place isn't safe.

615
00:36:12,641 --> 00:36:14,641
You're the one who stole the TARDIS
and ran away.

616
00:36:14,721 --> 00:36:17,081
The Captain might be needing you.

617
00:36:17,161 --> 00:36:19,441
No, the Captain"s fine.
Why did you do it?

618
00:36:19,521 --> 00:36:23,241
Oh, I'm sure your Doctor has explained.

619
00:36:24,761 --> 00:36:26,481
Not even sure he remembers.

620
00:36:26,561 --> 00:36:29,561
There were many pressing reasons.

621
00:36:30,241 --> 00:36:33,881
I don't mean what you ran away from.
What were you running to?

622
00:36:36,441 --> 00:36:38,361
That's rather a good question.

623
00:36:38,881 --> 00:36:40,321
Questions are kind of my thing.

624
00:36:41,641 --> 00:36:42,881
How are you with answers?

625
00:36:43,601 --> 00:36:45,001
Been a long time.

626
00:36:46,201 --> 00:36:47,841
Remember the good old days?

627
00:36:48,001 --> 00:36:50,881
When I got miniaturised
and climbed around inside you?

628
00:36:51,601 --> 00:36:55,161
You taught me to hate the Daleks.

629
00:36:56,041 --> 00:36:57,321
Billions of years ago.

630
00:36:57,401 --> 00:36:58,921
What have you been up to since then?

631
00:36:59,001 --> 00:37:00,801
Destroying Daleks.

632
00:37:00,881 --> 00:37:03,561
Yes, all the ones who come here
to murder you, yes.

633
00:37:03,641 --> 00:37:05,361
I saw the mess outside.

634
00:37:05,441 --> 00:37:07,161
Why are you here?

635
00:37:09,761 --> 00:37:11,921
As a Dalek,

636
00:37:12,001 --> 00:37:15,961
you are linked
in to the Dalek hive mind.

637
00:37:16,041 --> 00:37:17,721
All Daleks are.

638
00:37:18,921 --> 00:37:20,441
Biggest database I know.

639
00:37:21,081 --> 00:37:22,321
I'd like to access it.

640
00:37:22,721 --> 00:37:25,521
Why would I help you?

641
00:37:27,081 --> 00:37:32,361
Because helping me in any way

642
00:37:34,001 --> 00:37:35,481
does something wonderful.

643
00:37:39,241 --> 00:37:41,201
It hurts the Daleks.

644
00:37:42,441 --> 00:37:45,281
FIRST DOCTOR:
There is good and there is evil.

645
00:37:46,321 --> 00:37:49,321
I left Gallifrey
to answer a question of my own.

646
00:37:49,721 --> 00:37:53,481
By any analysis, evil should always win.

647
00:37:54,361 --> 00:37:58,481
Good is not
a practical survival strategy.

648
00:37:59,241 --> 00:38:01,881
It requires loyalty,

649
00:38:02,521 --> 00:38:05,361
self-sacrifice and, er, love.

650
00:38:05,961 --> 00:38:10,081
And so, why does good prevail?

651
00:38:10,481 --> 00:38:12,721
What keeps the balance
between good and evil

652
00:38:12,801 --> 00:38:15,321
in this appalling universe?

653
00:38:16,721 --> 00:38:20,881
Is there some kind of logic,
some mysterious force?

654
00:38:21,761 --> 00:38:24,241
Perhaps there's just a bloke.

655
00:38:24,761 --> 00:38:25,761
(MUMBLES)

656
00:38:26,241 --> 00:38:28,321
-A bloke?
-Yeah.

657
00:38:28,801 --> 00:38:33,201
Perhaps there's just some bloke
wandering around

658
00:38:33,281 --> 00:38:35,001
putting everything right
when it goes wrong.

659
00:38:35,441 --> 00:38:38,441
Well, that would be a nice story,
wouldn't it?

660
00:38:38,521 --> 00:38:39,721
That would be the best.

661
00:38:39,801 --> 00:38:42,881
But the real world is not a fairy tale.

662
00:38:43,561 --> 00:38:45,761
You dash around the universe

663
00:38:45,841 --> 00:38:47,561
trying to figure out
what's holding it all together

664
00:38:47,641 --> 00:38:50,841
and you really, really don't know.

665
00:38:51,481 --> 00:38:53,041
You know me in the future.

666
00:38:53,121 --> 00:38:55,121
Do I ever understand?

667
00:38:55,961 --> 00:38:56,961
No.

668
00:38:58,801 --> 00:39:00,441
I really don't think you do.

669
00:39:03,641 --> 00:39:05,481
Everyone who's ever met you does.

670
00:39:07,681 --> 00:39:09,121
You're amazing, Doctor.

671
00:39:10,161 --> 00:39:11,321
Never forget that.

672
00:39:12,081 --> 00:39:13,761
Never ever.

673
00:39:14,881 --> 00:39:17,721
Well, that's very kind of you.

674
00:39:17,801 --> 00:39:20,481
We just needed to
understand you, Doctor.

675
00:39:23,761 --> 00:39:25,681
"Professor Helen Clay.

676
00:39:25,761 --> 00:39:30,201
"University of New Earth,
year 5 billion and 12."

677
00:39:32,601 --> 00:39:34,841
There's footage, can you run it?

678
00:39:35,881 --> 00:39:37,041
A spy.

679
00:39:38,561 --> 00:39:39,841
A spy in the camp.

680
00:39:39,921 --> 00:39:41,241
No, not a spy.

681
00:39:43,041 --> 00:39:44,281
I'm Bill Potts.

682
00:39:44,921 --> 00:39:47,681
But I'm part of Testimony now.

683
00:39:49,601 --> 00:39:53,641
The Testimony Foundation combines
the resources of time travel

684
00:39:53,721 --> 00:39:57,281
with the latest
in memory extraction techniques.

685
00:39:57,921 --> 00:40:01,681
The near dead can be lifted momentarily
from their time streams,

686
00:40:01,801 --> 00:40:03,641
their memories duplicated,

687
00:40:03,721 --> 00:40:08,241
and then their physical souls returned
to the moment of their dissolution,

688
00:40:08,361 --> 00:40:12,761
without pain, distress
or any recall of the process.

689
00:40:14,001 --> 00:40:17,921
Now the dead can speak again.

690
00:40:18,601 --> 00:40:20,641
We can hear the testimony

691
00:40:20,721 --> 00:40:22,321
of the past.

692
00:40:22,561 --> 00:40:24,521
And channel led through
our glass avatars,

693
00:40:24,601 --> 00:40:27,761
they can walk among us again.

694
00:40:28,041 --> 00:40:31,841
This is Heaven on New Earth.

695
00:40:31,921 --> 00:40:33,121
(CRACKLING)

696
00:40:34,041 --> 00:40:35,761
It's not an evil plan.

697
00:40:36,841 --> 00:40:39,761
I don't really know what to do
when it isn't an evil plan.

698
00:40:41,161 --> 00:40:43,841
Why did you stop it? Rusty?

699
00:40:45,801 --> 00:40:49,801
He didn't stop it.
They've frozen time again.

700
00:40:50,081 --> 00:40:51,081
Who has?

701
00:40:53,241 --> 00:40:55,601
(HOLOGRAM HUMMING)

702
00:40:56,281 --> 00:40:57,881
Not everything's evil, Doctor.

703
00:40:57,961 --> 00:40:59,081
(WHOOSHING)

704
00:40:59,161 --> 00:41:01,041
You're not the only kind one
in the universe.

705
00:41:01,121 --> 00:41:02,121
I knew you weren't real.

706
00:41:02,521 --> 00:41:05,321
Oh, shut up and stop being so stupid!
Of course I'm real.

707
00:41:05,961 --> 00:41:08,521
What is anyone supposed to be
except a bunch of memories?

708
00:41:09,441 --> 00:41:13,401
These are my memories,
so this is me. I'm Bill Potts.

709
00:41:13,521 --> 00:41:14,801
And I'm back.

710
00:41:15,521 --> 00:41:17,121
And so long as I'm here,

711
00:41:18,241 --> 00:41:21,761
what the hell do you mean
you're not going to regenerate?

712
00:41:25,161 --> 00:41:26,721
There has to be an end, Bill.

713
00:41:27,201 --> 00:41:29,521
For everyone, everywhere.

714
00:41:30,841 --> 00:41:32,081
What about the Captain?

715
00:41:34,001 --> 00:41:37,281
You know he has to die at his allotted
point in time and space.

716
00:41:38,321 --> 00:41:40,041
To correct the error.

717
00:41:41,401 --> 00:41:43,641
I'm so tired of losing people.

718
00:41:45,441 --> 00:41:47,761
If the Captain has to die,

719
00:41:47,961 --> 00:41:50,921
a request... This was our fault.

720
00:41:51,161 --> 00:41:52,161
How so?

721
00:41:53,481 --> 00:41:54,961
Let us take him back.

722
00:41:55,321 --> 00:41:57,681
FIRST DOCTOR: How was this our fault?
DOCTOR: You and me

723
00:41:58,001 --> 00:42:00,481
tried to die twice
in the same lifetime.

724
00:42:01,281 --> 00:42:04,681
Our lives are woven
throughout time and space.

725
00:42:05,201 --> 00:42:08,841
We caused the time line error
that put the Captain in the wrong place.

726
00:42:09,001 --> 00:42:11,601
We created a whirlpool in time

727
00:42:11,841 --> 00:42:13,561
that landed him at our feet.

728
00:42:13,841 --> 00:42:18,001
But why him? What's so important
about one captain?

729
00:42:19,801 --> 00:42:21,961
Everybody is important to somebody,

730
00:42:23,241 --> 00:42:24,561
somewhere.

731
00:42:25,881 --> 00:42:27,241
Are you all right?

732
00:42:28,321 --> 00:42:30,441
Yes, I'm fine. Absolutely.

733
00:42:31,121 --> 00:42:32,241
Just thinking.

734
00:42:33,601 --> 00:42:35,401
I told the wife
I'd be home for Christmas.

735
00:42:36,961 --> 00:42:39,081
Funny how things work out.

736
00:43:05,521 --> 00:43:06,961
Thank you.

737
00:43:11,401 --> 00:43:14,521
Thank you, all.
You've all been most gracious

738
00:43:14,601 --> 00:43:16,201
under the unfortunate circumstances.

739
00:43:16,441 --> 00:43:18,561
I regret, Captain,

740
00:43:18,641 --> 00:43:21,481
that the universe generally

741
00:43:21,561 --> 00:43:24,121
fails to be a fairy tale.

742
00:43:24,441 --> 00:43:27,281
When time resumes,
you will not remember this.

743
00:43:27,361 --> 00:43:30,561
A perception filter
will also render us invisible.

744
00:43:31,761 --> 00:43:33,121
Yes.

745
00:43:33,201 --> 00:43:35,441
One imagines some
of those words were attached

746
00:43:35,561 --> 00:43:37,441
to actual meanings of some sort.

747
00:43:38,241 --> 00:43:41,161
One thing you could possibly
do for me if you're very kind?

748
00:43:41,721 --> 00:43:44,681
Oh, anything. Name it.

749
00:43:44,761 --> 00:43:47,761
My family. Perhaps you could

750
00:43:47,841 --> 00:43:49,961
look in on them
from time to time.

751
00:43:50,321 --> 00:43:52,681
We should be delighted...
(STAMMERS)

752
00:43:52,761 --> 00:43:55,321
-What's the name?
-Lethbridge-Stewart.

753
00:43:56,241 --> 00:43:58,761
Captain Archibald Hamish

754
00:43:58,881 --> 00:44:00,241
Lethbridge-Stewart.

755
00:44:00,321 --> 00:44:02,361
FIRST DOCTOR:
I shall make it my business.

756
00:44:03,441 --> 00:44:06,641
You can trust him on that.

757
00:44:07,281 --> 00:44:08,521
Thank you so much.

758
00:44:09,361 --> 00:44:11,801
I believe I am now ready.

759
00:44:31,161 --> 00:44:34,401
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

760
00:44:34,481 --> 00:44:36,121
Cold, isn't it?

761
00:44:39,001 --> 00:44:40,681
It's about to get colder, I suppose.

762
00:44:41,441 --> 00:44:42,481
For one of us.

763
00:44:42,681 --> 00:44:44,561
(WHIMPERING)

764
00:44:45,481 --> 00:44:47,441
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

765
00:44:47,521 --> 00:44:49,041
(GRUNTS)

766
00:44:52,961 --> 00:44:55,561
(MEN SING IN DISTANCE)

767
00:45:00,321 --> 00:45:02,001
(SINGING GETS LOUDER)

768
00:45:02,681 --> 00:45:03,961
I say...

769
00:45:06,041 --> 00:45:07,121
Is that singing?

770
00:45:12,681 --> 00:45:14,681
(MEN SINGING IN GERMAN)

771
00:45:26,201 --> 00:45:27,521
Is that...

772
00:45:28,121 --> 00:45:29,601
Christmas carols?

773
00:45:31,601 --> 00:45:34,881
# Silent night

774
00:45:35,521 --> 00:45:39,041
# Holy night

775
00:45:39,721 --> 00:45:43,481
# All is calm

776
00:45:43,721 --> 00:45:47,321
# All is bright

777
00:45:48,081 --> 00:45:51,881
# Round yon virgin

778
00:45:52,001 --> 00:45:53,121
# Mother and child #

779
00:45:53,201 --> 00:45:55,241
You know, I could swear
it's coming from both sides.

780
00:45:56,081 --> 00:45:59,921
If I've got my timings right,
and clearly I have,

781
00:46:00,241 --> 00:46:02,321
then we should be
right at the beginning.

782
00:46:02,401 --> 00:46:03,521
SOLDIER: Hold your fire.

783
00:46:03,601 --> 00:46:05,881
DOCTOR: I adjusted the time frame
only by a couple of hours.

784
00:46:05,961 --> 00:46:07,641
Any other day, it wouldn't
make any difference

785
00:46:07,761 --> 00:46:10,201
but this is Christmas 1914,

786
00:46:10,481 --> 00:46:13,801
and a human miracle
is about to happen.

787
00:46:14,801 --> 00:46:16,921
The Christmas armistice.

788
00:46:19,881 --> 00:46:21,921
(CHUCKLES)

789
00:46:24,281 --> 00:46:25,441
(GRUNTS)

790
00:46:27,241 --> 00:46:28,561
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

791
00:46:28,681 --> 00:46:30,241
Wounded man here!

792
00:46:30,361 --> 00:46:32,601
(BLOWS WHISTLE)

793
00:46:32,721 --> 00:46:34,481
Wounded man here!

794
00:46:34,561 --> 00:46:36,121
Wounded man.

795
00:46:36,281 --> 00:46:37,841
(BLOWS WHISTLE)

796
00:46:38,841 --> 00:46:40,361
DOCTOR: Never happened again,

797
00:46:40,481 --> 00:46:42,881
any war, anywhere.

798
00:46:42,961 --> 00:46:45,521
I say, wounded man here.

799
00:46:45,641 --> 00:46:47,121
Wounded man!

800
00:46:47,601 --> 00:46:49,321
DOCTOR: But for one day,

801
00:46:50,201 --> 00:46:53,801
one Christmas,
a very long time ago,

802
00:46:55,081 --> 00:46:57,441
everyone just put down their weapons

803
00:46:58,321 --> 00:47:00,201
and started to sing.

804
00:47:01,601 --> 00:47:03,361
Everybody just stopped.

805
00:47:04,881 --> 00:47:06,441
Everyone.

806
00:47:07,201 --> 00:47:08,801
It was just kind.

807
00:47:09,201 --> 00:47:11,401
FIRST DOCTOR: You've saved him.

808
00:47:12,561 --> 00:47:14,121
DOCTOR: Both of them.

809
00:47:14,681 --> 00:47:16,081
Never hurts.

810
00:47:16,241 --> 00:47:18,481
A couple fewer
dead people on the battlefield.

811
00:47:22,241 --> 00:47:25,641
So that's what it means
to be a Doctor

812
00:47:25,961 --> 00:47:27,761
of War.

813
00:47:28,561 --> 00:47:30,361
You were right, you know.

814
00:47:30,441 --> 00:47:33,641
The universe generally
fails to be a fairy tale.

815
00:47:34,401 --> 00:47:35,921
(SOLDIER GROANING)

816
00:47:36,401 --> 00:47:37,881
But that's where we come in.

817
00:47:38,801 --> 00:47:41,881
(SOLDIERS TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

818
00:47:42,761 --> 00:47:43,921
(CHEERING)

819
00:47:44,201 --> 00:47:46,481
# For auld lang syne, my dear

820
00:47:46,721 --> 00:47:49,881
# For auld lang syne

821
00:47:50,761 --> 00:47:54,441
# We'll take a cup of kindness yet

822
00:47:54,801 --> 00:47:57,841
# For auld lang syne

823
00:47:58,481 --> 00:48:02,321
# For auld lang syne, my dear

824
00:48:02,601 --> 00:48:06,001
# For auld lang syne

825
00:48:06,401 --> 00:48:10,161
# We'll take a cup of kindness yet

826
00:48:10,481 --> 00:48:13,201
# For auld lang syne #

827
00:48:13,281 --> 00:48:15,241
I think I'm ready now.

828
00:48:15,641 --> 00:48:17,841
But I should like to know...

829
00:48:19,201 --> 00:48:20,841
Are you?

830
00:48:21,521 --> 00:48:23,041
You'll find out.

831
00:48:24,041 --> 00:48:25,321
The long way round.

832
00:48:25,801 --> 00:48:27,361
Whatever you decide,

833
00:48:28,601 --> 00:48:30,881
good luck, Doctor.

834
00:48:33,001 --> 00:48:34,641
Goodbye, Doctor.

835
00:49:13,561 --> 00:49:14,641
(EXHALES)

836
00:49:29,561 --> 00:49:31,241
Well then...

837
00:49:33,321 --> 00:49:34,921
Here we go.

838
00:49:35,921 --> 00:49:38,241
The long way round.

839
00:50:13,281 --> 00:50:14,681
BILL: Are you okay?

840
00:50:19,481 --> 00:50:21,321
Shall we go for one last stroll,

841
00:50:22,121 --> 00:50:23,521
Miss Potts?

842
00:50:33,721 --> 00:50:36,001
You know what the hardest thing
about knowing you was?

843
00:50:37,441 --> 00:50:38,881
My superior intelligence.

844
00:50:39,561 --> 00:50:43,521
Bedazzling charisma...
Oh, my impeccable dress sense.

845
00:50:43,801 --> 00:50:45,321
Letting you go...

846
00:50:49,161 --> 00:50:52,921
Letting go of the Doctor
is so, so hard.

847
00:50:54,321 --> 00:50:55,681
Isn't it?

848
00:50:56,241 --> 00:51:00,001
You see, that's... That's not the sort
of thing the real Bill Potts would say.

849
00:51:00,401 --> 00:51:02,361
I am the real Bill!

850
00:51:02,521 --> 00:51:04,921
A life is just memories.
I'm all her memories.

851
00:51:05,481 --> 00:51:07,681
-So I'm her.
-If you say so.

852
00:51:07,961 --> 00:51:11,401
Okay, I'm gonna prove to you
how important memories are.

853
00:51:11,481 --> 00:51:13,081
I've got a little goodbye present
for you.

854
00:51:13,161 --> 00:51:15,721
Oh, that's nice. Will I have to pretend
to like it, because

855
00:51:15,801 --> 00:51:18,001
-honestly, that rug...
-Oh, come here, you.

856
00:51:24,401 --> 00:51:25,961
Merry Christmas, Doctor.

857
00:51:30,761 --> 00:51:32,001
Clara.

858
00:51:32,641 --> 00:51:33,721
Hello.

859
00:51:34,921 --> 00:51:36,281
You stupid old man.

860
00:51:36,921 --> 00:51:38,161
You're back.

861
00:51:39,361 --> 00:51:40,961
You're in my head.

862
00:51:43,681 --> 00:51:45,361
All my memories...

863
00:51:47,881 --> 00:51:49,001
are back.

864
00:51:49,361 --> 00:51:51,321
And don't go
forgetting me again, because...

865
00:51:53,121 --> 00:51:54,641
quite frankly, that was offensive.

866
00:51:57,081 --> 00:51:59,721
Memories. They're important, right?

867
00:51:59,801 --> 00:52:01,961
I know what you're thinking.

868
00:52:02,041 --> 00:52:03,521
Where is he?

869
00:52:04,081 --> 00:52:05,241
Hello, sir.

870
00:52:05,361 --> 00:52:06,761
When you're already dying

871
00:52:06,881 --> 00:52:09,321
you're entitled to think that your day
couldn't get any worse, but...

872
00:52:09,801 --> 00:52:11,361
here you are.

873
00:52:11,441 --> 00:52:13,841
And both of you are here.
How does that work?

874
00:52:14,801 --> 00:52:16,241
We can be everyone.

875
00:52:16,361 --> 00:52:17,801
-We are everyone.
-Mmm-hmm.

876
00:52:18,281 --> 00:52:19,521
Yes, good this, innit?

877
00:52:19,641 --> 00:52:22,121
Now I'm all made of glass,
not just my nipples.

878
00:52:22,401 --> 00:52:24,601
Yeah, they got my hair
a bit wrong, though, didn't they?

879
00:52:24,961 --> 00:52:26,321
You don't have any hair!

880
00:52:26,921 --> 00:52:28,081
I have invisible hair.

881
00:52:28,961 --> 00:52:30,801
Got a suggestion for you then.

882
00:52:31,121 --> 00:52:32,601
Oh, there's a novelty.

883
00:52:33,201 --> 00:52:34,401
Don't die.

884
00:52:34,641 --> 00:52:35,921
Because if you do,

885
00:52:36,241 --> 00:52:39,441
I think everybody in the universe
might just go cold.

886
00:52:41,641 --> 00:52:43,361
Can't I ever have peace?

887
00:52:43,681 --> 00:52:45,241
Can't I rest?

888
00:52:49,481 --> 00:52:50,641
Of course you can.

889
00:52:50,961 --> 00:52:52,441
It's your choice.

890
00:52:52,601 --> 00:52:54,081
Only yours.

891
00:52:55,001 --> 00:52:56,241
We understand.

892
00:52:56,721 --> 00:52:58,001
No.

893
00:52:59,001 --> 00:53:00,201
No, you don't.

894
00:53:01,561 --> 00:53:02,881
You're not even really here.

895
00:53:04,681 --> 00:53:06,121
You're just memories,

896
00:53:06,481 --> 00:53:07,721
held in glass.

897
00:53:09,281 --> 00:53:11,041
Do you know how many of you
I could fill?

898
00:53:11,481 --> 00:53:12,961
I would shatter you.

899
00:53:14,441 --> 00:53:16,681
My testimony would shatter all of you.

900
00:53:17,681 --> 00:53:19,081
A life this long,

901
00:53:19,161 --> 00:53:22,761
do you understand what it is?
It's a battlefield like this one.

902
00:53:24,681 --> 00:53:26,201
And it's empty.

903
00:53:28,401 --> 00:53:29,761
Because everyone else

904
00:53:30,361 --> 00:53:31,721
has fallen.

905
00:53:36,401 --> 00:53:39,081
Thank you, thank you both,

906
00:53:40,081 --> 00:53:42,041
for everything that
you were to me.

907
00:53:47,561 --> 00:53:49,441
What happens now,

908
00:53:50,281 --> 00:53:51,801
where I go

909
00:53:52,401 --> 00:53:53,481
now

910
00:53:55,201 --> 00:53:56,761
has to be alone.

911
00:54:08,041 --> 00:54:09,321
Cuddle.

912
00:54:21,761 --> 00:54:23,161
(SIGHS)

913
00:54:24,841 --> 00:54:27,281
Time to leave the battlefield.

914
00:54:37,121 --> 00:54:40,001
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

915
00:54:40,841 --> 00:54:45,081
Oh, there it is. Silly old universe.

916
00:54:46,721 --> 00:54:48,921
The more I save it,
the more it needs saving.

917
00:54:50,681 --> 00:54:52,001
It's a treadmill.

918
00:54:52,321 --> 00:54:54,641
(BEEPING)

919
00:54:55,241 --> 00:54:59,241
Yes, yes, I know they'll get it
all wrong without me.

920
00:55:00,601 --> 00:55:03,441
(BEEPING)

921
00:55:05,081 --> 00:55:08,521
Well, I suppose,
one more lifetime

922
00:55:09,441 --> 00:55:11,121
won't kill anyone.

923
00:55:14,241 --> 00:55:16,081
Well, except me.

924
00:55:24,761 --> 00:55:26,841
You wait a moment, Doctor.

925
00:55:27,681 --> 00:55:29,321
Let's get it right.

926
00:55:32,321 --> 00:55:34,481
I've got a few things
to say to you.

927
00:55:35,721 --> 00:55:37,601
Basic stuff first.

928
00:55:38,881 --> 00:55:41,681
Never be cruel, never be cowardly

929
00:55:42,601 --> 00:55:44,681
and never ever eat pears.

930
00:55:45,561 --> 00:55:47,041
Remember...

931
00:55:49,441 --> 00:55:51,881
Hate is always foolish.

932
00:55:52,001 --> 00:55:56,321
Love is always wise.

933
00:56:03,721 --> 00:56:06,441
Always try to be nice,

934
00:56:06,521 --> 00:56:08,921
and never fail to be kind.

935
00:56:09,121 --> 00:56:11,441
Oh, and...

936
00:56:11,761 --> 00:56:13,841
You mustn't tell anyone your name.

937
00:56:16,641 --> 00:56:19,361
No one would understand it anyway.

938
00:56:21,961 --> 00:56:23,401
Except...

939
00:56:23,481 --> 00:56:24,881
(GROANS)

940
00:56:31,481 --> 00:56:34,441
Except children.

941
00:56:36,801 --> 00:56:38,601
Children can hear it

942
00:56:39,161 --> 00:56:40,841
sometimes

943
00:56:41,881 --> 00:56:44,281
if their hearts are in the right place

944
00:56:45,881 --> 00:56:48,081
and the stars are, too.

945
00:56:49,961 --> 00:56:52,281
Children can hear your name.

946
00:56:52,641 --> 00:56:54,041
(GROANS)

947
00:56:56,081 --> 00:56:57,561
(GRUNTS)

948
00:57:01,201 --> 00:57:03,161
But nobody else...

949
00:57:04,281 --> 00:57:06,121
Nobody else...

950
00:57:06,761 --> 00:57:08,081
Ever...

951
00:57:12,761 --> 00:57:14,601
Laugh hard.

952
00:57:15,921 --> 00:57:17,481
Run fast.

953
00:57:19,081 --> 00:57:20,561
Be kind.

954
00:57:26,881 --> 00:57:28,361
Doctor...

955
00:57:31,521 --> 00:57:33,121
I let you go.

956
00:58:32,881 --> 00:58:34,601
Oh, brilliant.

957
00:58:36,681 --> 00:58:38,921
(BEEPING)

958
00:58:40,801 --> 00:58:42,561
(RUMBLING)

959
00:58:43,201 --> 00:58:45,761
Ah! Ah! Ah!

960
00:58:59,321 --> 00:59:01,241
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

961
00:59:04,921 --> 00:59:08,041
(SCREAMING)

962
00:59:21,001 --> 00:59:23,001
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

